                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/1113</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-11T18:00:00+00:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">December 11, 1914, 6 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7:20 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>1247. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> unofficially
                    expressed the hope to me that the bill introduced by Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGM1">Hitchcock</persName> in the Senate will not pass, aimed to
                    prohibit the exportation by private firms of munitions of war to any
                    belligerent. He calls attention to the fact that this would <pb facs="0893"
                        n="579" xml:id="pg_579"/> be special legislation passed while war is in
                    progress making a radical departure from a long-established custom and that for
                    this reason [it would appear?] an unneutral act towards the belligerents that
                    can profit by it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
